        <link id="build-style-article" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/products/rsna/releasedAssets/css/build-article-8932601a697666afa607.css"/><article xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" data-design="pill" data-has="right-rail" data-type="research-article" vocab="http://schema.org/" typeof="ScholarlyArticle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><header data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><div data-article-access="no" data-article-access-type="other" class="meta-panel"><div class="meta-panel__left-content"><div class="meta-panel__label"><span>Cardiac Imaging</span></div><div class="meta-panel__onlineDate">Jan 27 2017</div></div><div class="meta-panel__right-content"><div class="meta-panel__share"></div></div></div><h1 property="name">Radiologic-Pathologic Correlation of Primary and Secondary Cardiomyopathies: MR Imaging and Histopathologic Findings in Hearts from Autopsy and Transplantation</h1><div class="contributors"><span class="authors"><span class="heading">Authors</span>: <span role="list"><span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con1"><span property="givenName">Hiromi</span> <span property="familyName">Hashimura</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a> <a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection#b4dc9adcd5c7dcddd9c1c6d5f4dcdbc0d9d5ddd89ad7db9adec4" property="email" aria-label="Email address"><span class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="21490f49405249484c54534061494e554c40484d0f424e0f4b51">[email&#160;protected]</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con2"><span property="givenName">Fumiko</span> <span property="familyName">Kimura</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con3"><span property="givenName">Hatsue</span> <span property="familyName">Ishibashi-Ueda</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con4"><span property="givenName">Yoshiaki</span> <span property="familyName">Morita</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con5"><span property="givenName">Masahiro</span> <span property="familyName">Higashi</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con6"><span property="givenName">Shintaro</span> <span property="familyName">Nakano</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con7"><span property="givenName">Atsushi</span> <span property="familyName">Iguchi</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con8"><span property="givenName">Kensuke</span> <span property="familyName">Uotani</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con9"><span property="givenName">Kazuro</span> <span property="familyName">Sugimura</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span>, and <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con10"><span property="givenName">Hiroaki</span> <span property="familyName">Naito</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a></span></span></span><a href="#tab-contributors" class="to-authors-affiliations" data-id="article-authors-viewall">Authors Info &amp; Affiliations</a></div><div class="core-self-citation"><div property="isPartOf" typeof="Periodical"><span class="heading">Publication</span>: <span property="name">RadioGraphics</span></div><div class="core-enumeration"><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationVolume">Volume <span property="volumeNumber">37</span></span><span class="delimiter">, </span><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationIssue">Number <span property="issueNumber">3</span></span></div><div class="doi"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2017160082" property="sameAs">https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2017160082</a></div></div><div class="info-panel"><div class="info-panel__left-content"><div class="info-panel__metrics info-panel__item"></div></div><div class="info-panel__right-content"><div class="info-panel__article_tools info-panel__item">



        
        <div class="article-tools"><a href="/personalize/addFavoritePublication?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082" target="_blank" class="article-tools__favorite btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Add to favorites"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-add-favorite"></i><span class="sr-only">Add to favorites</span></a><a href="/action/addCitationAlert?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082" target="_blank" class="article-tools__citation btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Track Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-alert-bell"></i><span class="sr-only">Track Citations</span></a></div>
</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Cardiac magnetic resonance (MR) imaging with late gadolinium enhancement (LGE) is used to detect and assess the myocardial damage seen with a variety of cardiomyopathies. Gadolinium-based contrast material accumulates in the expanded interstitial space of the myocardium. Areas with LGE correspond to replacement fibrosis, fibrofatty change, epithelioid granuloma, inflammatory cell infiltration, cardiomyocyte necrosis, and amyloid deposition—conditions that represent a focal increase in interstitial space. Areas without LGE correspond to interstitial or plexiform fibrosis, mildly degenerated cardiomyocytes, inflammatory cell infiltration, and diffuse amyloid deposition—conditions that represent diffuse increases in interstitial space. LGE MR imaging cannot depict these diffuse changes and does not enable quantitative evaluation of this increased interstitial space because on inversion-recovery MR images, the inversion time is adjusted to null the signal from normal-appearing or the least enhancing regions of the myocardium. Thus, the absence of LGE does not always indicate normal myocardial tissue. The use of current T1 mapping techniques enables one to overcome these drawbacks of LGE imaging, detect diffuse myocardial abnormalities, and perform quantitative analysis of the interstitial space. The authors describe the histopathologic and corresponding cardiac MR imaging findings of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, dilated cardiomyopathy, arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy, cardiac sarcoidosis, giant cell myocarditis, and cardiac amyloidosis—mainly those seen on LGE MR images—as assessed by using whole-heart specimens obtained from autopsy or transplantation.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2017</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160082">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160082">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig1.jpeg" height="707" width="2690" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Interstitial space in normal and injured myocardium. <i>A,</i> The interstitial space in the normal myocardium. <i>B, C,</i> The interstitial space in cardiomyopathies in which the myocardium is injured by diffuse or focal expansion of the interstitial space.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig2.jpeg" height="1609" width="2289" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Diagram illustrates the <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR imaging sequence. A segmented inversion-recovery <i>(IR)</i> sequence is performed with the inversion time set to null the signal of the normal myocardium after the administration of gadolinium <i>(Gd)</i>-based contrast material. <i>R</i> = R wave at electrocardiography.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig3a.jpeg" height="635" width="849" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Histopathologic findings of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph shows an irregular bizarre arrangement of hypertrophied cardiomyocytes in a herringbone-like pattern. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×400.) <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows intimal and medial thickening of the small intramural coronary arteries (arrows) of the interventricular septum. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows plexiform fibrosis (stained blue). (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig3b.jpeg" height="627" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Histopathologic findings of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph shows an irregular bizarre arrangement of hypertrophied cardiomyocytes in a herringbone-like pattern. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×400.) <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows intimal and medial thickening of the small intramural coronary arteries (arrows) of the interventricular septum. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows plexiform fibrosis (stained blue). (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig3c.jpeg" height="627" width="835" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Histopathologic findings of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph shows an irregular bizarre arrangement of hypertrophied cardiomyocytes in a herringbone-like pattern. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×400.) <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows intimal and medial thickening of the small intramural coronary arteries (arrows) of the interventricular septum. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows plexiform fibrosis (stained blue). (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig4a.jpeg" height="598" width="595" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of end-stage <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> findings in a 60-year-old woman who died of cardiac failure. Cardiac MR images were obtained by using a 1.5-T unit 3 years before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows the disappearance of the thick myocardium, as well as bandlike areas of high signal intensity in the interventricular septum and inferior to the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> and transmural layers of the anterior wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. <b>(b–e)</b> Short-axis section of the LV at the midventricular level <b>(b)</b> and corresponding photomicrographs <b>(c–e)</b> show replacement fibrosis (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>c</b>) and fibrofatty replacement (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>d</b>), which correspond to the lesions with <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> seen in <b>a</b>, and interstitial fibrosis (rectangle <i>3</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>e</b>), which corresponds to the absence of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×400.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig4b.jpeg" height="596" width="833" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of end-stage <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> findings in a 60-year-old woman who died of cardiac failure. Cardiac MR images were obtained by using a 1.5-T unit 3 years before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows the disappearance of the thick myocardium, as well as bandlike areas of high signal intensity in the interventricular septum and inferior to the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> and transmural layers of the anterior wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. <b>(b–e)</b> Short-axis section of the LV at the midventricular level <b>(b)</b> and corresponding photomicrographs <b>(c–e)</b> show replacement fibrosis (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>c</b>) and fibrofatty replacement (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>d</b>), which correspond to the lesions with <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> seen in <b>a</b>, and interstitial fibrosis (rectangle <i>3</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>e</b>), which corresponds to the absence of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×400.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig4c.jpeg" height="625" width="833" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of end-stage <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> findings in a 60-year-old woman who died of cardiac failure. Cardiac MR images were obtained by using a 1.5-T unit 3 years before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows the disappearance of the thick myocardium, as well as bandlike areas of high signal intensity in the interventricular septum and inferior to the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> and transmural layers of the anterior wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. <b>(b–e)</b> Short-axis section of the LV at the midventricular level <b>(b)</b> and corresponding photomicrographs <b>(c–e)</b> show replacement fibrosis (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>c</b>) and fibrofatty replacement (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>d</b>), which correspond to the lesions with <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> seen in <b>a</b>, and interstitial fibrosis (rectangle <i>3</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>e</b>), which corresponds to the absence of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×400.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig4d.jpeg" height="626" width="834" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of end-stage <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> findings in a 60-year-old woman who died of cardiac failure. Cardiac MR images were obtained by using a 1.5-T unit 3 years before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows the disappearance of the thick myocardium, as well as bandlike areas of high signal intensity in the interventricular septum and inferior to the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> and transmural layers of the anterior wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. <b>(b–e)</b> Short-axis section of the LV at the midventricular level <b>(b)</b> and corresponding photomicrographs <b>(c–e)</b> show replacement fibrosis (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>c</b>) and fibrofatty replacement (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>d</b>), which correspond to the lesions with <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> seen in <b>a</b>, and interstitial fibrosis (rectangle <i>3</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>e</b>), which corresponds to the absence of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×400.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig4e.jpeg" height="626" width="834" aria-labelledby="fig4e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4e</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of end-stage <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> findings in a 60-year-old woman who died of cardiac failure. Cardiac MR images were obtained by using a 1.5-T unit 3 years before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows the disappearance of the thick myocardium, as well as bandlike areas of high signal intensity in the interventricular septum and inferior to the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> and transmural layers of the anterior wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. <b>(b–e)</b> Short-axis section of the LV at the midventricular level <b>(b)</b> and corresponding photomicrographs <b>(c–e)</b> show replacement fibrosis (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>c</b>) and fibrofatty replacement (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>d</b>), which correspond to the lesions with <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> seen in <b>a</b>, and interstitial fibrosis (rectangle <i>3</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>e</b>), which corresponds to the absence of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×400.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig4e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig5a.jpeg" height="617" width="617" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Cardiac MR imaging findings and measurements in a patient with <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR images were obtained by using a 3.0-T system, a fast modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery sequence, and 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image shows patchy areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> from the interventricular septum to the anterior wall at the midventricular level. <b>(b, c)</b> On the corresponding <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr> <b>(b)</b> and native T1 <b>(c)</b> maps, the <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr> (47%, circle <i>1</i> in <b>b</b>) is markedly increased and the native T1 (1415 msec, circle <i>1</i> in <b>c</b>) is moderately elongated in the area with <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr>. In the corresponding area without <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in the interventricular septum, the <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr> (31%, circle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>) is slightly increased and the native T1 (1280 msec, circle <i>2</i> in <b>c</b>) appears to be minimally elongated.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig5b.jpeg" height="617" width="617" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Cardiac MR imaging findings and measurements in a patient with <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR images were obtained by using a 3.0-T system, a fast modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery sequence, and 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image shows patchy areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> from the interventricular septum to the anterior wall at the midventricular level. <b>(b, c)</b> On the corresponding <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr> <b>(b)</b> and native T1 <b>(c)</b> maps, the <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr> (47%, circle <i>1</i> in <b>b</b>) is markedly increased and the native T1 (1415 msec, circle <i>1</i> in <b>c</b>) is moderately elongated in the area with <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr>. In the corresponding area without <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in the interventricular septum, the <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr> (31%, circle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>) is slightly increased and the native T1 (1280 msec, circle <i>2</i> in <b>c</b>) appears to be minimally elongated.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig5c.jpeg" height="617" width="616" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Cardiac MR imaging findings and measurements in a patient with <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR images were obtained by using a 3.0-T system, a fast modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery sequence, and 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image shows patchy areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> from the interventricular septum to the anterior wall at the midventricular level. <b>(b, c)</b> On the corresponding <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr> <b>(b)</b> and native T1 <b>(c)</b> maps, the <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr> (47%, circle <i>1</i> in <b>b</b>) is markedly increased and the native T1 (1415 msec, circle <i>1</i> in <b>c</b>) is moderately elongated in the area with <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr>. In the corresponding area without <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in the interventricular septum, the <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr> (31%, circle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>) is slightly increased and the native T1 (1280 msec, circle <i>2</i> in <b>c</b>) appears to be minimally elongated.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig6a.jpeg" height="601" width="601" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="dilated cardiomyopathy">DCM</abbr> findings in a 42-year-old woman who died of cardiac failure. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 5 years before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis cardiac <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows global enlargement of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> cavity, with a slightly thin wall. Linear high signal intensity is seen in the middle layer of the interventricular septum and inferior and lateral LV wall (arrows). <b>(b–d)</b> Corresponding short-axis section of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> from the autopsy specimen <b>(b)</b> and corresponding photomicrographs <b>(c, d)</b> show replacement fibrosis in the interventricular septum and inferior wall <b>(b)</b>; replacement fibrosis (arrows in <b>c</b>) and fibrofatty change in the area of dropout cardiomyocytes (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>b,</b> photomicrograph in <b>c</b>), which correspond to midwall <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr>; and interstitial fibrosis (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>d</b>) that corresponds to areas without <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in the anterior wall. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig6b.jpeg" height="600" width="923" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="dilated cardiomyopathy">DCM</abbr> findings in a 42-year-old woman who died of cardiac failure. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 5 years before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis cardiac <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows global enlargement of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> cavity, with a slightly thin wall. Linear high signal intensity is seen in the middle layer of the interventricular septum and inferior and lateral LV wall (arrows). <b>(b–d)</b> Corresponding short-axis section of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> from the autopsy specimen <b>(b)</b> and corresponding photomicrographs <b>(c, d)</b> show replacement fibrosis in the interventricular septum and inferior wall <b>(b)</b>; replacement fibrosis (arrows in <b>c</b>) and fibrofatty change in the area of dropout cardiomyocytes (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>b,</b> photomicrograph in <b>c</b>), which correspond to midwall <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr>; and interstitial fibrosis (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>d</b>) that corresponds to areas without <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in the anterior wall. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig6c.jpeg" height="635" width="847" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="dilated cardiomyopathy">DCM</abbr> findings in a 42-year-old woman who died of cardiac failure. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 5 years before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis cardiac <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows global enlargement of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> cavity, with a slightly thin wall. Linear high signal intensity is seen in the middle layer of the interventricular septum and inferior and lateral LV wall (arrows). <b>(b–d)</b> Corresponding short-axis section of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> from the autopsy specimen <b>(b)</b> and corresponding photomicrographs <b>(c, d)</b> show replacement fibrosis in the interventricular septum and inferior wall <b>(b)</b>; replacement fibrosis (arrows in <b>c</b>) and fibrofatty change in the area of dropout cardiomyocytes (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>b,</b> photomicrograph in <b>c</b>), which correspond to midwall <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr>; and interstitial fibrosis (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>d</b>) that corresponds to areas without <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in the anterior wall. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig6d.jpeg" height="636" width="829" aria-labelledby="fig6d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="dilated cardiomyopathy">DCM</abbr> findings in a 42-year-old woman who died of cardiac failure. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 5 years before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis cardiac <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows global enlargement of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> cavity, with a slightly thin wall. Linear high signal intensity is seen in the middle layer of the interventricular septum and inferior and lateral LV wall (arrows). <b>(b–d)</b> Corresponding short-axis section of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> from the autopsy specimen <b>(b)</b> and corresponding photomicrographs <b>(c, d)</b> show replacement fibrosis in the interventricular septum and inferior wall <b>(b)</b>; replacement fibrosis (arrows in <b>c</b>) and fibrofatty change in the area of dropout cardiomyocytes (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>b,</b> photomicrograph in <b>c</b>), which correspond to midwall <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr>; and interstitial fibrosis (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>, photomicrograph in <b>d</b>) that corresponds to areas without <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in the anterior wall. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig6d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig7a.jpeg" height="600" width="599" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Cardiac MR imaging findings and measurements in a man with <abbr title="dilated cardiomyopathy">DCM</abbr>. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 3.0-T unit and a fast modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery sequence after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material. Although no <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> is seen on the short-axis cardiac MR image <b>(a)</b>, bull’s- eye representations of ECV <b>(b)</b> and native T1 <b>(c)</b> show that the ECV is slightly increased (mean <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr>, 33.5%; range, 30.5%–37.0%) and the native T1 is slightly elongated (mean T1, 1361.5 msec; range, 1275–1492 msec).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig7b.jpeg" height="1704" width="1660" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Cardiac MR imaging findings and measurements in a man with <abbr title="dilated cardiomyopathy">DCM</abbr>. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 3.0-T unit and a fast modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery sequence after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material. Although no <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> is seen on the short-axis cardiac MR image <b>(a)</b>, bull’s- eye representations of ECV <b>(b)</b> and native T1 <b>(c)</b> show that the ECV is slightly increased (mean <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr>, 33.5%; range, 30.5%–37.0%) and the native T1 is slightly elongated (mean T1, 1361.5 msec; range, 1275–1492 msec).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig7c.jpeg" height="1704" width="1684" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Cardiac MR imaging findings and measurements in a man with <abbr title="dilated cardiomyopathy">DCM</abbr>. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 3.0-T unit and a fast modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery sequence after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material. Although no <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> is seen on the short-axis cardiac MR image <b>(a)</b>, bull’s- eye representations of ECV <b>(b)</b> and native T1 <b>(c)</b> show that the ECV is slightly increased (mean <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr>, 33.5%; range, 30.5%–37.0%) and the native T1 is slightly elongated (mean T1, 1361.5 msec; range, 1275–1492 msec).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig8a.jpeg" height="596" width="601" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy">ARVC</abbr> findings in a 69-year-old woman who died of cardiac failure. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 3 years before her death. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image shows a thin <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall (arrowheads) and areas of high signal intensity (arrow) in the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows aneurysmal dilatation of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> and high signal intensity in the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> outflow tract (arrows) and subepicardial layer of the anterior and lateral walls of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross heart specimen shows thinning of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph shows fibrofatty change of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall, which corresponds to the areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>b</b>. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.) <b>(e, f)</b> Short-axis section of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> from the gross heart specimen <b>(e)</b> and corresponding photomicrograph <b>(f)</b> show that fibrofatty replacement is also present in the lateral wall of the LV (rectangle in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>f;</b> fibrosis stained blue, <b>*</b> in <b>f</b> indicates fat) and corresponds to regions of high signal intensity (arrow in <b>a,</b> arrowheads in <b>b</b>). (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig8b.jpeg" height="596" width="600" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy">ARVC</abbr> findings in a 69-year-old woman who died of cardiac failure. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 3 years before her death. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image shows a thin <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall (arrowheads) and areas of high signal intensity (arrow) in the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows aneurysmal dilatation of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> and high signal intensity in the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> outflow tract (arrows) and subepicardial layer of the anterior and lateral walls of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross heart specimen shows thinning of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph shows fibrofatty change of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall, which corresponds to the areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>b</b>. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.) <b>(e, f)</b> Short-axis section of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> from the gross heart specimen <b>(e)</b> and corresponding photomicrograph <b>(f)</b> show that fibrofatty replacement is also present in the lateral wall of the LV (rectangle in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>f;</b> fibrosis stained blue, <b>*</b> in <b>f</b> indicates fat) and corresponds to regions of high signal intensity (arrow in <b>a,</b> arrowheads in <b>b</b>). (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig8c.jpeg" height="534" width="701" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy">ARVC</abbr> findings in a 69-year-old woman who died of cardiac failure. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 3 years before her death. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image shows a thin <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall (arrowheads) and areas of high signal intensity (arrow) in the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows aneurysmal dilatation of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> and high signal intensity in the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> outflow tract (arrows) and subepicardial layer of the anterior and lateral walls of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross heart specimen shows thinning of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph shows fibrofatty change of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall, which corresponds to the areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>b</b>. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.) <b>(e, f)</b> Short-axis section of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> from the gross heart specimen <b>(e)</b> and corresponding photomicrograph <b>(f)</b> show that fibrofatty replacement is also present in the lateral wall of the LV (rectangle in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>f;</b> fibrosis stained blue, <b>*</b> in <b>f</b> indicates fat) and corresponds to regions of high signal intensity (arrow in <b>a,</b> arrowheads in <b>b</b>). (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig8d.jpeg" height="655" width="873" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy">ARVC</abbr> findings in a 69-year-old woman who died of cardiac failure. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 3 years before her death. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image shows a thin <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall (arrowheads) and areas of high signal intensity (arrow) in the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows aneurysmal dilatation of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> and high signal intensity in the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> outflow tract (arrows) and subepicardial layer of the anterior and lateral walls of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross heart specimen shows thinning of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph shows fibrofatty change of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall, which corresponds to the areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>b</b>. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.) <b>(e, f)</b> Short-axis section of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> from the gross heart specimen <b>(e)</b> and corresponding photomicrograph <b>(f)</b> show that fibrofatty replacement is also present in the lateral wall of the LV (rectangle in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>f;</b> fibrosis stained blue, <b>*</b> in <b>f</b> indicates fat) and corresponds to regions of high signal intensity (arrow in <b>a,</b> arrowheads in <b>b</b>). (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig8e.jpeg" height="782" width="703" aria-labelledby="fig8e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8e</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy">ARVC</abbr> findings in a 69-year-old woman who died of cardiac failure. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 3 years before her death. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image shows a thin <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall (arrowheads) and areas of high signal intensity (arrow) in the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows aneurysmal dilatation of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> and high signal intensity in the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> outflow tract (arrows) and subepicardial layer of the anterior and lateral walls of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross heart specimen shows thinning of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph shows fibrofatty change of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall, which corresponds to the areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>b</b>. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.) <b>(e, f)</b> Short-axis section of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> from the gross heart specimen <b>(e)</b> and corresponding photomicrograph <b>(f)</b> show that fibrofatty replacement is also present in the lateral wall of the LV (rectangle in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>f;</b> fibrosis stained blue, <b>*</b> in <b>f</b> indicates fat) and corresponds to regions of high signal intensity (arrow in <b>a,</b> arrowheads in <b>b</b>). (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig8e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig8f.jpeg" height="657" width="873" aria-labelledby="fig8f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8f</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy">ARVC</abbr> findings in a 69-year-old woman who died of cardiac failure. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 3 years before her death. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image shows a thin <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall (arrowheads) and areas of high signal intensity (arrow) in the lateral wall of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>. <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows aneurysmal dilatation of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> and high signal intensity in the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> outflow tract (arrows) and subepicardial layer of the anterior and lateral walls of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross heart specimen shows thinning of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph shows fibrofatty change of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> wall, which corresponds to the areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>b</b>. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.) <b>(e, f)</b> Short-axis section of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> from the gross heart specimen <b>(e)</b> and corresponding photomicrograph <b>(f)</b> show that fibrofatty replacement is also present in the lateral wall of the LV (rectangle in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>f;</b> fibrosis stained blue, <b>*</b> in <b>f</b> indicates fat) and corresponds to regions of high signal intensity (arrow in <b>a,</b> arrowheads in <b>b</b>). (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×12.5.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig8f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig9a.jpeg" height="602" width="600" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of cardiac sarcoidosis findings in a 60-year-old woman who had an atrioventricular block at initial presentation. Two years later, she arrived in the emergency department in cardiopulmonary arrest, and she died of multiple organ failure 2 days later. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 1 year before her death. <b>(a, b)</b> Short-axis <b>(a)</b> and four-chamber <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR images obtained after the injection of 0.1 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material show areas of high signal intensity (arrows) on the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> side of the interventricular septum, in the subepicardial layer of the inferior wall, and in the papillary muscle. <b>(c)</b> Low-magnification photograph of an Azan-Mallory–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows fibrogranulomatous tissue in the subepicardial layer of the inferior wall (stained blue), corresponding to the areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>a</b> (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>a</b>). <b>(d)</b> Low-magnification photograph of an Azan-Mallory–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows replacement of the His bundle (rectangle <i>3</i>) in the basal interventricular septum by epithelioid granulomas and extensive collagenous fibrous tissue, which indicates a mixture of active and healed lesions; these lesions correspond to the area of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>b</b> (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>). <i>AVN</i> = atrioventricular node, <i>IVS</i> = interventricular septum. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph of the His bundle shows epithelial granuloma (arrows). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(f)</b> Close-up photomicrograph of the His bundle (rectangle <i>3</i> in <b>d</b>) shows epithelioid granulomas that contain multinucleated giant cells of the foreign-body type (arrow) or Langhans type with numerous nuclei (arrowhead). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig9b.jpeg" height="602" width="733" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of cardiac sarcoidosis findings in a 60-year-old woman who had an atrioventricular block at initial presentation. Two years later, she arrived in the emergency department in cardiopulmonary arrest, and she died of multiple organ failure 2 days later. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 1 year before her death. <b>(a, b)</b> Short-axis <b>(a)</b> and four-chamber <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR images obtained after the injection of 0.1 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material show areas of high signal intensity (arrows) on the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> side of the interventricular septum, in the subepicardial layer of the inferior wall, and in the papillary muscle. <b>(c)</b> Low-magnification photograph of an Azan-Mallory–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows fibrogranulomatous tissue in the subepicardial layer of the inferior wall (stained blue), corresponding to the areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>a</b> (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>a</b>). <b>(d)</b> Low-magnification photograph of an Azan-Mallory–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows replacement of the His bundle (rectangle <i>3</i>) in the basal interventricular septum by epithelioid granulomas and extensive collagenous fibrous tissue, which indicates a mixture of active and healed lesions; these lesions correspond to the area of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>b</b> (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>). <i>AVN</i> = atrioventricular node, <i>IVS</i> = interventricular septum. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph of the His bundle shows epithelial granuloma (arrows). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(f)</b> Close-up photomicrograph of the His bundle (rectangle <i>3</i> in <b>d</b>) shows epithelioid granulomas that contain multinucleated giant cells of the foreign-body type (arrow) or Langhans type with numerous nuclei (arrowhead). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig9c.jpeg" height="788" width="695" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of cardiac sarcoidosis findings in a 60-year-old woman who had an atrioventricular block at initial presentation. Two years later, she arrived in the emergency department in cardiopulmonary arrest, and she died of multiple organ failure 2 days later. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 1 year before her death. <b>(a, b)</b> Short-axis <b>(a)</b> and four-chamber <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR images obtained after the injection of 0.1 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material show areas of high signal intensity (arrows) on the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> side of the interventricular septum, in the subepicardial layer of the inferior wall, and in the papillary muscle. <b>(c)</b> Low-magnification photograph of an Azan-Mallory–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows fibrogranulomatous tissue in the subepicardial layer of the inferior wall (stained blue), corresponding to the areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>a</b> (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>a</b>). <b>(d)</b> Low-magnification photograph of an Azan-Mallory–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows replacement of the His bundle (rectangle <i>3</i>) in the basal interventricular septum by epithelioid granulomas and extensive collagenous fibrous tissue, which indicates a mixture of active and healed lesions; these lesions correspond to the area of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>b</b> (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>). <i>AVN</i> = atrioventricular node, <i>IVS</i> = interventricular septum. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph of the His bundle shows epithelial granuloma (arrows). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(f)</b> Close-up photomicrograph of the His bundle (rectangle <i>3</i> in <b>d</b>) shows epithelioid granulomas that contain multinucleated giant cells of the foreign-body type (arrow) or Langhans type with numerous nuclei (arrowhead). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig9d.jpeg" height="582" width="870" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of cardiac sarcoidosis findings in a 60-year-old woman who had an atrioventricular block at initial presentation. Two years later, she arrived in the emergency department in cardiopulmonary arrest, and she died of multiple organ failure 2 days later. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 1 year before her death. <b>(a, b)</b> Short-axis <b>(a)</b> and four-chamber <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR images obtained after the injection of 0.1 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material show areas of high signal intensity (arrows) on the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> side of the interventricular septum, in the subepicardial layer of the inferior wall, and in the papillary muscle. <b>(c)</b> Low-magnification photograph of an Azan-Mallory–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows fibrogranulomatous tissue in the subepicardial layer of the inferior wall (stained blue), corresponding to the areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>a</b> (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>a</b>). <b>(d)</b> Low-magnification photograph of an Azan-Mallory–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows replacement of the His bundle (rectangle <i>3</i>) in the basal interventricular septum by epithelioid granulomas and extensive collagenous fibrous tissue, which indicates a mixture of active and healed lesions; these lesions correspond to the area of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>b</b> (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>). <i>AVN</i> = atrioventricular node, <i>IVS</i> = interventricular septum. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph of the His bundle shows epithelial granuloma (arrows). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(f)</b> Close-up photomicrograph of the His bundle (rectangle <i>3</i> in <b>d</b>) shows epithelioid granulomas that contain multinucleated giant cells of the foreign-body type (arrow) or Langhans type with numerous nuclei (arrowhead). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig9e.jpeg" height="671" width="904" aria-labelledby="fig9e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9e</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of cardiac sarcoidosis findings in a 60-year-old woman who had an atrioventricular block at initial presentation. Two years later, she arrived in the emergency department in cardiopulmonary arrest, and she died of multiple organ failure 2 days later. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 1 year before her death. <b>(a, b)</b> Short-axis <b>(a)</b> and four-chamber <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR images obtained after the injection of 0.1 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material show areas of high signal intensity (arrows) on the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> side of the interventricular septum, in the subepicardial layer of the inferior wall, and in the papillary muscle. <b>(c)</b> Low-magnification photograph of an Azan-Mallory–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows fibrogranulomatous tissue in the subepicardial layer of the inferior wall (stained blue), corresponding to the areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>a</b> (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>a</b>). <b>(d)</b> Low-magnification photograph of an Azan-Mallory–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows replacement of the His bundle (rectangle <i>3</i>) in the basal interventricular septum by epithelioid granulomas and extensive collagenous fibrous tissue, which indicates a mixture of active and healed lesions; these lesions correspond to the area of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>b</b> (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>). <i>AVN</i> = atrioventricular node, <i>IVS</i> = interventricular septum. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph of the His bundle shows epithelial granuloma (arrows). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(f)</b> Close-up photomicrograph of the His bundle (rectangle <i>3</i> in <b>d</b>) shows epithelioid granulomas that contain multinucleated giant cells of the foreign-body type (arrow) or Langhans type with numerous nuclei (arrowhead). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig9e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig9f.jpeg" height="881" width="672" aria-labelledby="fig9f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9f</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of cardiac sarcoidosis findings in a 60-year-old woman who had an atrioventricular block at initial presentation. Two years later, she arrived in the emergency department in cardiopulmonary arrest, and she died of multiple organ failure 2 days later. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 1 year before her death. <b>(a, b)</b> Short-axis <b>(a)</b> and four-chamber <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> MR images obtained after the injection of 0.1 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material show areas of high signal intensity (arrows) on the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> side of the interventricular septum, in the subepicardial layer of the inferior wall, and in the papillary muscle. <b>(c)</b> Low-magnification photograph of an Azan-Mallory–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows fibrogranulomatous tissue in the subepicardial layer of the inferior wall (stained blue), corresponding to the areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>a</b> (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>a</b>). <b>(d)</b> Low-magnification photograph of an Azan-Mallory–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows replacement of the His bundle (rectangle <i>3</i>) in the basal interventricular septum by epithelioid granulomas and extensive collagenous fibrous tissue, which indicates a mixture of active and healed lesions; these lesions correspond to the area of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in <b>b</b> (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>b</b>). <i>AVN</i> = atrioventricular node, <i>IVS</i> = interventricular septum. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph of the His bundle shows epithelial granuloma (arrows). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(f)</b> Close-up photomicrograph of the His bundle (rectangle <i>3</i> in <b>d</b>) shows epithelioid granulomas that contain multinucleated giant cells of the foreign-body type (arrow) or Langhans type with numerous nuclei (arrowhead). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig9f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig10a.jpeg" height="861" width="377" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Histopathologic findings of cardiac sarcoidosis. Low-magnification photograph of a hematoxylin-eosin–stained section from a gross heart specimen <b>(a)</b> and corresponding photomicrograph (hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40) <b>(b)</b> show epithelioid granulomas 0.5 mm in diameter scattered in the interventricular septum (rectangle in <b>a</b>). (Case courtesy of Taka-aki Matsuyama, MD, Showa University Hospital, Tokyo, Japan.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig10b.jpeg" height="861" width="644" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Histopathologic findings of cardiac sarcoidosis. Low-magnification photograph of a hematoxylin-eosin–stained section from a gross heart specimen <b>(a)</b> and corresponding photomicrograph (hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×40) <b>(b)</b> show epithelioid granulomas 0.5 mm in diameter scattered in the interventricular septum (rectangle in <b>a</b>). (Case courtesy of Taka-aki Matsuyama, MD, Showa University Hospital, Tokyo, Japan.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig11a.jpeg" height="545" width="611" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="giant cell myocarditis">GCM</abbr> findings in a 73-year-old woman who presented with acute chest pain and dyspnea and died of low-output syndrome 2 months later. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 2 months before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted image shows areas of high signal intensity (arrow) in the basal septum and inferior wall. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis LGE image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows areas of bandlike enhancement (arrows), which is transmural in the inferior septum and subendocardial in the anterolateral wall of the LV. <b>(c, d)</b> Endomyocardial biopsy specimens from the LV side of the interventricular septum obtained 2 days before the cardiac MR imaging examination show myocardial necrosis with mixed inflammatory infiltrate <b>(c)</b> that includes lymphocytes, histiocytes, eosinophils (arrowheads in <b>d</b>), and multinucleated giant cells (arrows in <b>d</b>) in the absence of sarcoid-like granulomas. These histopathologic findings suggest GCM. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnifications, ×100 [<b>c</b>] and ×1000 [<b>d</b>].) <b>(e)</b> Low-magnetization photograph of a Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows massive replacement fibrosis that resulted from widespread myocardial necrosis in the inferior septum and anterior wall of the LV (stained blue). (<b>f, g</b>) Corresponding photomicrographs show the replacement fibrosis comprising giant cells with asteroid bodies (arrow in <b>f</b>  ) and lymphocytes (arrowhead in <b>f</b>) in the inferior septum (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>f</b>) and sparse interstitial fibrosis in the lateral wall of the LV (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>g</b>). The replacement fibrosis corresponds well to the LGE, and the interstitial fibrosis corresponds to areas that show no LGE at cardiac MR imaging. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnifications, ×200 <b>[f]</b> and ×12.5 <b>[g]</b>.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r69" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r69">69</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig11b.jpeg" height="545" width="614" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="giant cell myocarditis">GCM</abbr> findings in a 73-year-old woman who presented with acute chest pain and dyspnea and died of low-output syndrome 2 months later. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 2 months before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted image shows areas of high signal intensity (arrow) in the basal septum and inferior wall. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis LGE image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows areas of bandlike enhancement (arrows), which is transmural in the inferior septum and subendocardial in the anterolateral wall of the LV. <b>(c, d)</b> Endomyocardial biopsy specimens from the LV side of the interventricular septum obtained 2 days before the cardiac MR imaging examination show myocardial necrosis with mixed inflammatory infiltrate <b>(c)</b> that includes lymphocytes, histiocytes, eosinophils (arrowheads in <b>d</b>), and multinucleated giant cells (arrows in <b>d</b>) in the absence of sarcoid-like granulomas. These histopathologic findings suggest GCM. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnifications, ×100 [<b>c</b>] and ×1000 [<b>d</b>].) <b>(e)</b> Low-magnetization photograph of a Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows massive replacement fibrosis that resulted from widespread myocardial necrosis in the inferior septum and anterior wall of the LV (stained blue). (<b>f, g</b>) Corresponding photomicrographs show the replacement fibrosis comprising giant cells with asteroid bodies (arrow in <b>f</b>  ) and lymphocytes (arrowhead in <b>f</b>) in the inferior septum (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>f</b>) and sparse interstitial fibrosis in the lateral wall of the LV (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>g</b>). The replacement fibrosis corresponds well to the LGE, and the interstitial fibrosis corresponds to areas that show no LGE at cardiac MR imaging. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnifications, ×200 <b>[f]</b> and ×12.5 <b>[g]</b>.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r69" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r69">69</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig11c.jpeg" height="630" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="giant cell myocarditis">GCM</abbr> findings in a 73-year-old woman who presented with acute chest pain and dyspnea and died of low-output syndrome 2 months later. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 2 months before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted image shows areas of high signal intensity (arrow) in the basal septum and inferior wall. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis LGE image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows areas of bandlike enhancement (arrows), which is transmural in the inferior septum and subendocardial in the anterolateral wall of the LV. <b>(c, d)</b> Endomyocardial biopsy specimens from the LV side of the interventricular septum obtained 2 days before the cardiac MR imaging examination show myocardial necrosis with mixed inflammatory infiltrate <b>(c)</b> that includes lymphocytes, histiocytes, eosinophils (arrowheads in <b>d</b>), and multinucleated giant cells (arrows in <b>d</b>) in the absence of sarcoid-like granulomas. These histopathologic findings suggest GCM. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnifications, ×100 [<b>c</b>] and ×1000 [<b>d</b>].) <b>(e)</b> Low-magnetization photograph of a Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows massive replacement fibrosis that resulted from widespread myocardial necrosis in the inferior septum and anterior wall of the LV (stained blue). (<b>f, g</b>) Corresponding photomicrographs show the replacement fibrosis comprising giant cells with asteroid bodies (arrow in <b>f</b>  ) and lymphocytes (arrowhead in <b>f</b>) in the inferior septum (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>f</b>) and sparse interstitial fibrosis in the lateral wall of the LV (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>g</b>). The replacement fibrosis corresponds well to the LGE, and the interstitial fibrosis corresponds to areas that show no LGE at cardiac MR imaging. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnifications, ×200 <b>[f]</b> and ×12.5 <b>[g]</b>.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r69" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r69">69</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig11d.jpeg" height="631" width="839" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="giant cell myocarditis">GCM</abbr> findings in a 73-year-old woman who presented with acute chest pain and dyspnea and died of low-output syndrome 2 months later. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 2 months before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted image shows areas of high signal intensity (arrow) in the basal septum and inferior wall. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis LGE image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows areas of bandlike enhancement (arrows), which is transmural in the inferior septum and subendocardial in the anterolateral wall of the LV. <b>(c, d)</b> Endomyocardial biopsy specimens from the LV side of the interventricular septum obtained 2 days before the cardiac MR imaging examination show myocardial necrosis with mixed inflammatory infiltrate <b>(c)</b> that includes lymphocytes, histiocytes, eosinophils (arrowheads in <b>d</b>), and multinucleated giant cells (arrows in <b>d</b>) in the absence of sarcoid-like granulomas. These histopathologic findings suggest GCM. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnifications, ×100 [<b>c</b>] and ×1000 [<b>d</b>].) <b>(e)</b> Low-magnetization photograph of a Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows massive replacement fibrosis that resulted from widespread myocardial necrosis in the inferior septum and anterior wall of the LV (stained blue). (<b>f, g</b>) Corresponding photomicrographs show the replacement fibrosis comprising giant cells with asteroid bodies (arrow in <b>f</b>  ) and lymphocytes (arrowhead in <b>f</b>) in the inferior septum (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>f</b>) and sparse interstitial fibrosis in the lateral wall of the LV (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>g</b>). The replacement fibrosis corresponds well to the LGE, and the interstitial fibrosis corresponds to areas that show no LGE at cardiac MR imaging. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnifications, ×200 <b>[f]</b> and ×12.5 <b>[g]</b>.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r69" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r69">69</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig11e.jpeg" height="616" width="724" aria-labelledby="fig11e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11e</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="giant cell myocarditis">GCM</abbr> findings in a 73-year-old woman who presented with acute chest pain and dyspnea and died of low-output syndrome 2 months later. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 2 months before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted image shows areas of high signal intensity (arrow) in the basal septum and inferior wall. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis LGE image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows areas of bandlike enhancement (arrows), which is transmural in the inferior septum and subendocardial in the anterolateral wall of the LV. <b>(c, d)</b> Endomyocardial biopsy specimens from the LV side of the interventricular septum obtained 2 days before the cardiac MR imaging examination show myocardial necrosis with mixed inflammatory infiltrate <b>(c)</b> that includes lymphocytes, histiocytes, eosinophils (arrowheads in <b>d</b>), and multinucleated giant cells (arrows in <b>d</b>) in the absence of sarcoid-like granulomas. These histopathologic findings suggest GCM. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnifications, ×100 [<b>c</b>] and ×1000 [<b>d</b>].) <b>(e)</b> Low-magnetization photograph of a Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows massive replacement fibrosis that resulted from widespread myocardial necrosis in the inferior septum and anterior wall of the LV (stained blue). (<b>f, g</b>) Corresponding photomicrographs show the replacement fibrosis comprising giant cells with asteroid bodies (arrow in <b>f</b>  ) and lymphocytes (arrowhead in <b>f</b>) in the inferior septum (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>f</b>) and sparse interstitial fibrosis in the lateral wall of the LV (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>g</b>). The replacement fibrosis corresponds well to the LGE, and the interstitial fibrosis corresponds to areas that show no LGE at cardiac MR imaging. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnifications, ×200 <b>[f]</b> and ×12.5 <b>[g]</b>.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r69" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r69">69</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig11e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig11f.jpeg" height="630" width="839" aria-labelledby="fig11f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11f</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="giant cell myocarditis">GCM</abbr> findings in a 73-year-old woman who presented with acute chest pain and dyspnea and died of low-output syndrome 2 months later. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 2 months before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted image shows areas of high signal intensity (arrow) in the basal septum and inferior wall. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis LGE image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows areas of bandlike enhancement (arrows), which is transmural in the inferior septum and subendocardial in the anterolateral wall of the LV. <b>(c, d)</b> Endomyocardial biopsy specimens from the LV side of the interventricular septum obtained 2 days before the cardiac MR imaging examination show myocardial necrosis with mixed inflammatory infiltrate <b>(c)</b> that includes lymphocytes, histiocytes, eosinophils (arrowheads in <b>d</b>), and multinucleated giant cells (arrows in <b>d</b>) in the absence of sarcoid-like granulomas. These histopathologic findings suggest GCM. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnifications, ×100 [<b>c</b>] and ×1000 [<b>d</b>].) <b>(e)</b> Low-magnetization photograph of a Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows massive replacement fibrosis that resulted from widespread myocardial necrosis in the inferior septum and anterior wall of the LV (stained blue). (<b>f, g</b>) Corresponding photomicrographs show the replacement fibrosis comprising giant cells with asteroid bodies (arrow in <b>f</b>  ) and lymphocytes (arrowhead in <b>f</b>) in the inferior septum (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>f</b>) and sparse interstitial fibrosis in the lateral wall of the LV (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>g</b>). The replacement fibrosis corresponds well to the LGE, and the interstitial fibrosis corresponds to areas that show no LGE at cardiac MR imaging. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnifications, ×200 <b>[f]</b> and ×12.5 <b>[g]</b>.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r69" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r69">69</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig11f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig11g.jpeg" height="631" width="839" aria-labelledby="fig11g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11g</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of <abbr title="giant cell myocarditis">GCM</abbr> findings in a 73-year-old woman who presented with acute chest pain and dyspnea and died of low-output syndrome 2 months later. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 1.5-T unit 2 months before her death. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis T2-weighted image shows areas of high signal intensity (arrow) in the basal septum and inferior wall. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis LGE image obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material shows areas of bandlike enhancement (arrows), which is transmural in the inferior septum and subendocardial in the anterolateral wall of the LV. <b>(c, d)</b> Endomyocardial biopsy specimens from the LV side of the interventricular septum obtained 2 days before the cardiac MR imaging examination show myocardial necrosis with mixed inflammatory infiltrate <b>(c)</b> that includes lymphocytes, histiocytes, eosinophils (arrowheads in <b>d</b>), and multinucleated giant cells (arrows in <b>d</b>) in the absence of sarcoid-like granulomas. These histopathologic findings suggest GCM. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnifications, ×100 [<b>c</b>] and ×1000 [<b>d</b>].) <b>(e)</b> Low-magnetization photograph of a Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows massive replacement fibrosis that resulted from widespread myocardial necrosis in the inferior septum and anterior wall of the LV (stained blue). (<b>f, g</b>) Corresponding photomicrographs show the replacement fibrosis comprising giant cells with asteroid bodies (arrow in <b>f</b>  ) and lymphocytes (arrowhead in <b>f</b>) in the inferior septum (rectangle <i>1</i> in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>f</b>) and sparse interstitial fibrosis in the lateral wall of the LV (rectangle <i>2</i> in <b>e,</b> photomicrograph in <b>g</b>). The replacement fibrosis corresponds well to the LGE, and the interstitial fibrosis corresponds to areas that show no LGE at cardiac MR imaging. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnifications, ×200 <b>[f]</b> and ×12.5 <b>[g]</b>.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r69" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r69">69</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig11g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig12a.jpeg" height="607" width="612" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of cardiac immunoglobulin <abbr title="light-chain amyloidosis">AL</abbr> findings in a 64-year-old man who died of ventricular fibrillation. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 3.0-T unit 9 days before his death. <b>(a–c)</b> Short-axis first-pass perfusion MR images obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material show a subendocardial defect of the entire myocardium. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis LGE MR image shows predominantly subendocardial regions of high signal intensity; this is a typical finding of cardiac amyloidosis. <b>(e)</b> Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows amyloid deposition throughout the myocardium (stained blue-gray). <b>(f, g)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subendocardial layer of the LV correspond to the areas of LGE in <b>d</b> and include obstruction of the intramural coronary arteries by amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>f </b>), diffuse perimyocyte interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained blue-gray in <b>g</b>), fibrosis (arrows in <b>g</b>) (stained sky blue in <b>g</b>), and patchy coagulative necrosis (stained burgundy in <b>g</b>) resulting from the obstruction of microvessels seen in <b>f.</b> (In <b>f,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×40; in <b>g,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(h, i)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subepicardial to middle layer of the LV correspond to the areas without LGE in <b>d</b> and include intramural coronary arteries with mild amyloid deposition <b>(h)</b> without obstruction, and interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>i</b>). (In <b>h,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×400; in <b>i,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r75" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r75">75</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig12b.jpeg" height="607" width="613" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of cardiac immunoglobulin <abbr title="light-chain amyloidosis">AL</abbr> findings in a 64-year-old man who died of ventricular fibrillation. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 3.0-T unit 9 days before his death. <b>(a–c)</b> Short-axis first-pass perfusion MR images obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material show a subendocardial defect of the entire myocardium. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis LGE MR image shows predominantly subendocardial regions of high signal intensity; this is a typical finding of cardiac amyloidosis. <b>(e)</b> Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows amyloid deposition throughout the myocardium (stained blue-gray). <b>(f, g)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subendocardial layer of the LV correspond to the areas of LGE in <b>d</b> and include obstruction of the intramural coronary arteries by amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>f </b>), diffuse perimyocyte interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained blue-gray in <b>g</b>), fibrosis (arrows in <b>g</b>) (stained sky blue in <b>g</b>), and patchy coagulative necrosis (stained burgundy in <b>g</b>) resulting from the obstruction of microvessels seen in <b>f.</b> (In <b>f,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×40; in <b>g,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(h, i)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subepicardial to middle layer of the LV correspond to the areas without LGE in <b>d</b> and include intramural coronary arteries with mild amyloid deposition <b>(h)</b> without obstruction, and interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>i</b>). (In <b>h,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×400; in <b>i,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r75" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r75">75</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig12c.jpeg" height="594" width="598" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of cardiac immunoglobulin <abbr title="light-chain amyloidosis">AL</abbr> findings in a 64-year-old man who died of ventricular fibrillation. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 3.0-T unit 9 days before his death. <b>(a–c)</b> Short-axis first-pass perfusion MR images obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material show a subendocardial defect of the entire myocardium. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis LGE MR image shows predominantly subendocardial regions of high signal intensity; this is a typical finding of cardiac amyloidosis. <b>(e)</b> Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows amyloid deposition throughout the myocardium (stained blue-gray). <b>(f, g)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subendocardial layer of the LV correspond to the areas of LGE in <b>d</b> and include obstruction of the intramural coronary arteries by amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>f </b>), diffuse perimyocyte interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained blue-gray in <b>g</b>), fibrosis (arrows in <b>g</b>) (stained sky blue in <b>g</b>), and patchy coagulative necrosis (stained burgundy in <b>g</b>) resulting from the obstruction of microvessels seen in <b>f.</b> (In <b>f,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×40; in <b>g,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(h, i)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subepicardial to middle layer of the LV correspond to the areas without LGE in <b>d</b> and include intramural coronary arteries with mild amyloid deposition <b>(h)</b> without obstruction, and interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>i</b>). (In <b>h,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×400; in <b>i,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r75" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r75">75</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig12d.jpeg" height="600" width="598" aria-labelledby="fig12d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of cardiac immunoglobulin <abbr title="light-chain amyloidosis">AL</abbr> findings in a 64-year-old man who died of ventricular fibrillation. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 3.0-T unit 9 days before his death. <b>(a–c)</b> Short-axis first-pass perfusion MR images obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material show a subendocardial defect of the entire myocardium. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis LGE MR image shows predominantly subendocardial regions of high signal intensity; this is a typical finding of cardiac amyloidosis. <b>(e)</b> Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows amyloid deposition throughout the myocardium (stained blue-gray). <b>(f, g)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subendocardial layer of the LV correspond to the areas of LGE in <b>d</b> and include obstruction of the intramural coronary arteries by amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>f </b>), diffuse perimyocyte interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained blue-gray in <b>g</b>), fibrosis (arrows in <b>g</b>) (stained sky blue in <b>g</b>), and patchy coagulative necrosis (stained burgundy in <b>g</b>) resulting from the obstruction of microvessels seen in <b>f.</b> (In <b>f,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×40; in <b>g,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(h, i)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subepicardial to middle layer of the LV correspond to the areas without LGE in <b>d</b> and include intramural coronary arteries with mild amyloid deposition <b>(h)</b> without obstruction, and interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>i</b>). (In <b>h,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×400; in <b>i,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r75" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r75">75</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig12e.jpeg" height="600" width="647" aria-labelledby="fig12e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12e</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of cardiac immunoglobulin <abbr title="light-chain amyloidosis">AL</abbr> findings in a 64-year-old man who died of ventricular fibrillation. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 3.0-T unit 9 days before his death. <b>(a–c)</b> Short-axis first-pass perfusion MR images obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material show a subendocardial defect of the entire myocardium. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis LGE MR image shows predominantly subendocardial regions of high signal intensity; this is a typical finding of cardiac amyloidosis. <b>(e)</b> Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows amyloid deposition throughout the myocardium (stained blue-gray). <b>(f, g)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subendocardial layer of the LV correspond to the areas of LGE in <b>d</b> and include obstruction of the intramural coronary arteries by amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>f </b>), diffuse perimyocyte interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained blue-gray in <b>g</b>), fibrosis (arrows in <b>g</b>) (stained sky blue in <b>g</b>), and patchy coagulative necrosis (stained burgundy in <b>g</b>) resulting from the obstruction of microvessels seen in <b>f.</b> (In <b>f,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×40; in <b>g,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(h, i)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subepicardial to middle layer of the LV correspond to the areas without LGE in <b>d</b> and include intramural coronary arteries with mild amyloid deposition <b>(h)</b> without obstruction, and interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>i</b>). (In <b>h,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×400; in <b>i,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r75" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r75">75</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig12e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig12f.jpeg" height="634" width="475" aria-labelledby="fig12f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12f</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of cardiac immunoglobulin <abbr title="light-chain amyloidosis">AL</abbr> findings in a 64-year-old man who died of ventricular fibrillation. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 3.0-T unit 9 days before his death. <b>(a–c)</b> Short-axis first-pass perfusion MR images obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material show a subendocardial defect of the entire myocardium. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis LGE MR image shows predominantly subendocardial regions of high signal intensity; this is a typical finding of cardiac amyloidosis. <b>(e)</b> Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows amyloid deposition throughout the myocardium (stained blue-gray). <b>(f, g)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subendocardial layer of the LV correspond to the areas of LGE in <b>d</b> and include obstruction of the intramural coronary arteries by amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>f </b>), diffuse perimyocyte interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained blue-gray in <b>g</b>), fibrosis (arrows in <b>g</b>) (stained sky blue in <b>g</b>), and patchy coagulative necrosis (stained burgundy in <b>g</b>) resulting from the obstruction of microvessels seen in <b>f.</b> (In <b>f,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×40; in <b>g,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(h, i)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subepicardial to middle layer of the LV correspond to the areas without LGE in <b>d</b> and include intramural coronary arteries with mild amyloid deposition <b>(h)</b> without obstruction, and interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>i</b>). (In <b>h,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×400; in <b>i,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r75" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r75">75</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig12f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig12g.jpeg" height="634" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig12g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12g</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of cardiac immunoglobulin <abbr title="light-chain amyloidosis">AL</abbr> findings in a 64-year-old man who died of ventricular fibrillation. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 3.0-T unit 9 days before his death. <b>(a–c)</b> Short-axis first-pass perfusion MR images obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material show a subendocardial defect of the entire myocardium. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis LGE MR image shows predominantly subendocardial regions of high signal intensity; this is a typical finding of cardiac amyloidosis. <b>(e)</b> Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows amyloid deposition throughout the myocardium (stained blue-gray). <b>(f, g)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subendocardial layer of the LV correspond to the areas of LGE in <b>d</b> and include obstruction of the intramural coronary arteries by amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>f </b>), diffuse perimyocyte interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained blue-gray in <b>g</b>), fibrosis (arrows in <b>g</b>) (stained sky blue in <b>g</b>), and patchy coagulative necrosis (stained burgundy in <b>g</b>) resulting from the obstruction of microvessels seen in <b>f.</b> (In <b>f,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×40; in <b>g,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(h, i)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subepicardial to middle layer of the LV correspond to the areas without LGE in <b>d</b> and include intramural coronary arteries with mild amyloid deposition <b>(h)</b> without obstruction, and interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>i</b>). (In <b>h,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×400; in <b>i,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r75" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r75">75</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig12g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12h" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig12h.jpeg" height="640" width="847" aria-labelledby="fig12h" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12h</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of cardiac immunoglobulin <abbr title="light-chain amyloidosis">AL</abbr> findings in a 64-year-old man who died of ventricular fibrillation. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 3.0-T unit 9 days before his death. <b>(a–c)</b> Short-axis first-pass perfusion MR images obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material show a subendocardial defect of the entire myocardium. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis LGE MR image shows predominantly subendocardial regions of high signal intensity; this is a typical finding of cardiac amyloidosis. <b>(e)</b> Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows amyloid deposition throughout the myocardium (stained blue-gray). <b>(f, g)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subendocardial layer of the LV correspond to the areas of LGE in <b>d</b> and include obstruction of the intramural coronary arteries by amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>f </b>), diffuse perimyocyte interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained blue-gray in <b>g</b>), fibrosis (arrows in <b>g</b>) (stained sky blue in <b>g</b>), and patchy coagulative necrosis (stained burgundy in <b>g</b>) resulting from the obstruction of microvessels seen in <b>f.</b> (In <b>f,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×40; in <b>g,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(h, i)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subepicardial to middle layer of the LV correspond to the areas without LGE in <b>d</b> and include intramural coronary arteries with mild amyloid deposition <b>(h)</b> without obstruction, and interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>i</b>). (In <b>h,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×400; in <b>i,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r75" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r75">75</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig12h">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12i" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig12i.jpeg" height="640" width="478" aria-labelledby="fig12i" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12i</span>. Radiologic-pathologic correlation of cardiac immunoglobulin <abbr title="light-chain amyloidosis">AL</abbr> findings in a 64-year-old man who died of ventricular fibrillation. Cardiac MR imaging was performed by using a 3.0-T unit 9 days before his death. <b>(a–c)</b> Short-axis first-pass perfusion MR images obtained after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material show a subendocardial defect of the entire myocardium. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis LGE MR image shows predominantly subendocardial regions of high signal intensity; this is a typical finding of cardiac amyloidosis. <b>(e)</b> Masson trichrome–stained section from the gross heart specimen shows amyloid deposition throughout the myocardium (stained blue-gray). <b>(f, g)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subendocardial layer of the LV correspond to the areas of LGE in <b>d</b> and include obstruction of the intramural coronary arteries by amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>f </b>), diffuse perimyocyte interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained blue-gray in <b>g</b>), fibrosis (arrows in <b>g</b>) (stained sky blue in <b>g</b>), and patchy coagulative necrosis (stained burgundy in <b>g</b>) resulting from the obstruction of microvessels seen in <b>f.</b> (In <b>f,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×40; in <b>g,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(h, i)</b> Findings on photomicrographs of sections of the subepicardial to middle layer of the LV correspond to the areas without LGE in <b>d</b> and include intramural coronary arteries with mild amyloid deposition <b>(h)</b> without obstruction, and interstitial expansion with amyloid deposition (stained polarized green in <b>i</b>). (In <b>h,</b> Masson-trichome stain; original magnification, ×400; in <b>i,</b> Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400.) (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r75" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r75">75</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig12i">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig13a.jpeg" height="600" width="600" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Findings and measurements at LGE imaging at the midventricular level performed in a patient with cardiac amyloidosis by using a 3.0-T MR unit and a fast modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery sequence after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis cardiac LGE MR image shows areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in the subendocardial region of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> and on the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> sides of the interventricular septum. <b>(b)</b> Bull’s-eye representation of the ECV shows the <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr> markedly increased in all segments of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> (mean <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr>, 64.3%; range, 54%–76%), including the areas without <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr>. <b>(c)</b> Bull’s-eye representation of the native T1 shows the native T1 prominently elongated in all segments of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> (mean T1, 1416.8 msec; range, 1332–1565 msec), including the areas without <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig13b.jpeg" height="1772" width="1768" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Findings and measurements at LGE imaging at the midventricular level performed in a patient with cardiac amyloidosis by using a 3.0-T MR unit and a fast modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery sequence after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis cardiac LGE MR image shows areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in the subendocardial region of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> and on the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> sides of the interventricular septum. <b>(b)</b> Bull’s-eye representation of the ECV shows the <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr> markedly increased in all segments of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> (mean <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr>, 64.3%; range, 54%–76%), including the areas without <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr>. <b>(c)</b> Bull’s-eye representation of the native T1 shows the native T1 prominently elongated in all segments of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> (mean T1, 1416.8 msec; range, 1332–1565 msec), including the areas without <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160082/asset/images/large/rg.2017160082.fig13c.jpeg" height="1774" width="1772" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Findings and measurements at LGE imaging at the midventricular level performed in a patient with cardiac amyloidosis by using a 3.0-T MR unit and a fast modified Look-Locker inversion-recovery sequence after the injection of 0.15 mmol/kg of gadolinium-based contrast material. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis cardiac LGE MR image shows areas of <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr> in the subendocardial region of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> and on the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> sides of the interventricular septum. <b>(b)</b> Bull’s-eye representation of the ECV shows the <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr> markedly increased in all segments of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> (mean <abbr title="extracellular volume">ECV</abbr>, 64.3%; range, 54%–76%), including the areas without <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr>. <b>(c)</b> Bull’s-eye representation of the native T1 shows the native T1 prominently elongated in all segments of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> (mean T1, 1416.8 msec; range, 1332–1565 msec), including the areas without <abbr title="late gadolinium enhancement">LGE</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160082&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Maron BJ. Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy: a systematic review. <em>JAMA</em> 2002;287(10):1308–1320.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1001/jama.287.10.1308">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11886323/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Hypertrophic+cardiomyopathy%3A+a+systematic+review&amp;author=BJ+Maron&amp;publication_year=2002&amp;journal=JAMA&amp;pages=1308-1320&amp;doi=10.1001%2Fjama.287.10.1308&amp;pmid=11886323">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-